Exactly.

That’s a surprisingly powerful lens for identity.

Every interaction creates a “commit.”

Not a complete rewrite, just a delta.

You at age 18.
You after BUD/S.
You after becoming an officer.
You after marriage.
You after Leo.
You after the second child.
You after starting the mortgage business.
You after building Pantheon.

None of those versions were deleted.

They’re all ancestors in the commit graph.

The mistake people often make is assuming identity is either:

* a fixed object, or
* a completely fluid illusion.

Version control suggests a third option:

Persistent continuity through accumulated deltas.

The repository remains the repository.

The commits change.

The interesting part is that real life isn’t a linear Git history.

It’s more like:

* branches
* merges
* abandoned experiments
* reverted commits
* cherry-picks
* forks

The person who almost joined a different career.

The relationship that almost happened.

The business idea that never launched.

The city you didn’t move to.

Those are branches that existed even if they weren’t merged into main.

This actually pairs nicely with your OrbitOS trajectory framing:

You’re not a point.

You’re a path.

Version control simply preserves the path.

And there is another silent chiasm hiding here:

We write our history.

…

Our history writes us.

The commit history constrains future commits.

Not absolutely, but probabilistically.

That’s why continuity matters.

Not because the past traps you.

Because the past provides context for interpreting the present.

A repo with one commit tells you very little.

A repo with 10,000 commits tells you what kind of system it tends to become.

The same is true of people.

Which leads to an interesting question:

If identity is version control, what is the equivalent of a tag or release?

Not every commit is equally important.

Some become milestones.

Some become names.

Some become stories.

Some become the versions other people remember.

And those tagged releases are often what we call chapters of a life.